#Plotting my GDP data I’m plotting my data into a graph to show the GDP (BNP in danish) development in Denmark from 1970-2021 Using geom_col() to show the development. Also using the scale_x_continuous function I found on https://www.statology.org/ggplot2-scale_x_continuous/ to make the visualization more precise.

ggplot(data = BNP1) + 
  geom_col(aes(x = Year, y = BNP)) +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(-6, 6, by = 1)) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1970, 2022, by = 4)) +
  labs(title = 'BNP development')

##Trying another visualization To get another overlook I plot my data again, this time using geom_line()

ggplot(data = BNP1) + 
  geom_line(aes(x = Year, y = BNP, color = 'Red')) +
    scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(-6, 6, by = 1)) +
    scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1970, 2022, by = 4)) ##Husk at kildehenvise koden

#Plotting overall election results Now I am plotting my data on election results from 1971-2019 using geom_col() and adding color.

ggplot(data = Voting3) +
  geom_col(aes(x = Year, y = Percentage_of_votes, color = Party, fill=Party)) + 
  labs(title = "Voting Percentage")
## Warning: Removed 120 rows containing missing values (`position_stack()`).

#Plotting overall election results again To get a clearer and more pleasing visualization, I use geom_line() this time

ggplot(data = Voting3) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(x = Year, y = Percentage_of_votes, color = Party)) +
  labs(title = "Voting")
## Warning: Removed 119 rows containing missing values (`geom_line()`).

##Merging the parties into groups The visualization above is a bit messy, because of all the different parties, so in order to make the visualizations simpler and more transparent, I will merge the different parties into three groups. Left-wing parties, right-wing parties and center parties. ’

I will use the filter() function so merge the different groups

Left_wing <- Voting3 %>% 
  filter(Party == "SF" | Party == "EL" | Party == "ALT" | Party == "VS" | Party == "DKP" | Party == "FK")

Now visualizing the data left-wing data with geom_line

ggplot(data = Left_wing) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(x = Year, y = Percentage_of_votes, color = Party)) +
  labs(title = "Left wing votes 1971-2019")
## Warning: Removed 58 rows containing missing values (`geom_line()`).

Now doing the same with right-wing parties

Right_wing <- Voting3 %>% 
  filter(Party == "DF" | Party == "FP" | Party == "NB" | Party == "LA")

Visualizing the right-wing votes

ggplot(data = Right_wing) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(x = Year, y = Percentage_of_votes, color = Party)) +
  labs(title = "Right wing votes 1971-2019")
## Warning: Removed 48 rows containing missing values (`geom_line()`).

Merging the danish danish centre parties

Centre_parties <- Voting3 %>% 
  filter(Party == "S" | Party == "V" | Party == "KF" | Party == "RV" | Party == "CD" | Party == "DR" | Party == "KRF/KD")

Visualizing the center-parties

ggplot(data = Centre_parties) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(x = Year, y = Percentage_of_votes, color = Party)) +
  labs(title = "Centre votes 1971-2019")
## Warning: Removed 13 rows containing missing values (`geom_line()`).

##Summarizing my Left, Center and Right-wing votes in order to make the final visualisation more straightforward Summarizing my center parties

Centre_parties_summarized <- Centre_parties %>% 
  drop_na(Percentage_of_votes) %>% 
  group_by(Year) %>% 
  summarise(total_block_votes_pct = sum(Percentage_of_votes))

Summarizing the Left Wing votes into one group.

Left_parties_summarized <- Left_wing %>%
  drop_na(Percentage_of_votes) %>% 
  group_by(Year) %>% 
  summarise(total_block_votes_pct = sum(Percentage_of_votes))

Summarizing the Right Wing votes into one gruop

Right_parties_summarized <- Right_wing %>% 
  drop_na(Percentage_of_votes) %>% 
  group_by(Year) %>% 
  summarise(total_block_votes_pct = sum(Percentage_of_votes))

##Visualizating the three groups Now showing the three groups together with geom_line()

ggplot() + 
   geom_line(data = Left_parties_summarized, aes(x = Year, y = total_block_votes_pct, color = "Left-wing")) + 
  geom_line(data = Right_parties_summarized, aes(x = Year, y = total_block_votes_pct, color = "Right -wing")) + 
  geom_line(data = Centre_parties_summarized, aes( x= Year, y = total_block_votes_pct, color = "Centre-parties")) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1970, 2022, by = 4))

##Visualizing GDP development and voting trends together Applying multiple dataframes to show GDP development and election results together and making them easier to compare.

ggplot() + 
  geom_line(data = Left_parties_summarized, aes(x = Year, y = total_block_votes_pct, color = "Left-wing")) + 
  geom_line(data = Right_parties_summarized, aes(x = Year, y = total_block_votes_pct, color = "Right -wing")) + 
  geom_line(data = Centre_parties_summarized, aes( x= Year, y = total_block_votes_pct, color = "Centre-parties")) + 
  geom_line(data = BNP1, aes(x = Year, y = BNP1$BNP, color = "BNP")) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1970, 2022, by = 4))

#Conclusion I can now see if there is any correlation between the fluctuation in the GDP development and election results.
